{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11886"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.12,0.31,0.45,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105411"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4486"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87838"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2744"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45576"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105411"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a complaint of a midline, retrosternal, squeezing and pressure-like chest pain that began 25 minutes ago while he was actively exercising at home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of coronary artery disease, hypertension, and hyperlipidaemia. His regular medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, bisoprolol, and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis vital signs are stable. An ECG shows non-specific changes. His initial troponin was 0.04 ng/mL. His troponin and ECG are repeated six hours later and the troponin shows a level of 0.99 ng/mL, with ST elevations in V1-V4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt this time, he is urgently taken to the cardiac catheterisation lab. An 65% occlusion of the proximal left anterior descending artery is found on angiography, and the patient receives a drug eluting stent. He is started on dual antiplatelet therapy and monitored as an inpatient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFour days after his myocardial infarction, he again complains of some substernal chest discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate test to evaluate for cardiac chest pain at this time?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heart-type fatty acid binding protein","LDH","Myoglobin","Troponin","AST"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients where re-infarction is suspected following an initial myocardial infarction, immediate measurement of\u003Cstrong\u003E cardiac troponins\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended. Troponin levels typically start to elevate in the circulation within 2-3 hours of the onset of chest pain. The levels will continue to rise at that time until a peak is reached, generally between 12-48 hours. The troponin level will then begin to fall over the next 4-10 days down to a normal level. This expected rise and fall of the troponin is an important factor that can distinguish a myocardial infarction from other causes of elevated troponins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe isoenzyme of creatine kinase, CK-MB, can be useful in the evaluation of acute myocardial infarction, but it is much less sensitive and specific than cardiac troponins. Since CK-MB normalises 48 to 72 hours after an episode of myocardial ischaemia, as opposed to troponins, which can remain elevated for several days, CK-MB estimation\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be useful in detecting re-infarction if levels rise after an initial fall. However, in this case, CK-MB estimation was not done at the onset of the illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeart-type fatty acid binding protein\u003C/strong\u003E (H-FABP) is a sensitive biomarker for myocardial infarction and can be detected in the blood within one to three hours of the pain. H-FABP is recommended to be measured with troponin to identify myocardial infarction and acute coronary syndrome in patients presenting with chest pain. It is not used for the detection of reinfarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAST\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the liver, heart, skeletal muscles, brain, and kidneys. Due to its lack of specificity to the cardiac tissue, it is no longer used for the diagnosis of acute myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELDH\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific marker for cardiac myocytes, and its levels can also increase in many other conditions, LDH\u00a0is no longer used in the\u00a0diagnosis\u00a0of myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyoglobin \u003C/strong\u003Etesting has largely been discontinued in clinical laboratories since troponin assays have increased in sensitivity and can now be used to rule in acute myocardial infarction earlier in the patient\u2019s clinical course.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reinfarction is difficult to detect with any biomarker","In patients where re-infarction is suspected following an initial myocardial infarction, immediate measurement of cardiac troponins is recommended"],"references":["Kim, S.Y., Lee, JP., Shin, WR. et al. Cardiac biomarkers and detection methods for myocardial infarction. Mol. Cell. Toxicol. 18, 443\u2013455 (2022). Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36105117/","Khalil, H. Traditional and novel diagnostic biomarkers for acute myocardial infarction. Egypt J Intern Med 34, 87 (2022). Available from: https://ejim.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s43162-022-00178-w","Potter JM, Hickman PE, Cullen L. Troponins in myocardial infarction and injury. Aust Prescr 2022;45:53-7. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35592367/","National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes 2016. Heart, Lung and Circulation 2016; 25:895\u2013951. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27476580/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87838"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87838"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-09T00:39:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-09T08:15:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4486"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105411"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024